What's inside each container (not just a bare Linux box):
dockerfileFROM python:3.11-slim AS base

# Pre-install the tools candidates will use
RUN pip install langgraph langchain anthropic openai \
    httpx pytest black ruff

# Pre-configured mock tools (search, calculator, etc.)
# So candidates don't need API keys — the tools are wired
# to controlled mock services that the test defines
COPY ./mock_tools/ /app/tools/

# Starter code from test config
COPY ./starter_code/ /app/

# A small HTTP server that accepts code execution requests
# and streams stdout/stderr back over WebSocket
COPY ./execution_server.py /app/

# Resource limits enforced at container level
# (not just ulimit — actual cgroup limits)
CMD ["python", "/app/execution_server.py"]
Why "Network: proxied" is critical:

You don't want candidates calling real OpenAI/Anthropic in their code (cost, unpredictability)
Instead: your platform intercepts all outbound API calls via a proxy
This proxy logs every model call (prompt sent, response received)
This is how you evaluate "Prompt Quality" — you literally see the prompts

Candidate's code calls: openai.chat.completions.create(...)
                              ↓
              Your Proxy intercepts this call
                              ↓
              Logs: { prompt, model, timestamp, candidateId }
                              ↓
              Forwards to real OpenAI (with YOUR API key)
                              ↓
              Returns response to candidate's code
                              ↓
              Logs: { response, tokens_used, latency }
This is your real scoring data. Not just "did the code work" but "how did they prompt the model" — which is exactly what HackerRank cannot see.

Layer 3: The Session Recorder
Every action in the sandbox gets streamed to a time-series event log:
javascript// Every event has this shape
{
  sessionId: 'sess_abc123',
  candidateId: 'cand_xyz',
  testId: 'test_1',
  timestamp: 1717500000000,   // milliseconds, for replay ordering
  eventType: 'PROMPT_SENT',   // see all types below
  payload: {
    prompt: 'Build a search agent that...',
    model: 'claude-sonnet-4-6',
    file: 'main.py'
  }
}

// Event types you track:
PROMPT_SENT          // candidate sent a prompt to a model
MODEL_RESPONSE       // model returned code/text
CODE_ACCEPTED        // candidate clicked Accept on generated code
CODE_REJECTED        // candidate clicked Reject
CODE_MODIFIED        // candidate edited generated code before accepting
FILE_SAVED           // any file save
CODE_EXECUTED        // candidate hit Run
EXECUTION_OUTPUT     // stdout/stderr came back
TEST_CASE_RESULT     // a test case passed or failed
TERMINAL_COMMAND     // candidate typed in terminal
ERROR_ENCOUNTERED    // runtime error occurred
ERROR_RECOVERED      // they fixed it and re-ran
SESSION_SUBMITTED    // candidate clicked Submit
Why this matters: After submission, you can replay the entire session like a video. The recruiter sees not just the final code, but:

First prompt at 00:02:14
Rejected the first response
Second prompt refined at 00:08:45
Accepted, ran code, got an error
Fixed it themselves (didn't re-prompt) — that's Error Recovery: 9/10


