What each agent's prompt actually looks like:
PROMPT QUALITY AGENT:

You are evaluating a software engineering candidate's ability
to effectively prompt AI models during an agentic coding test.

Here are all the prompts they sent during the test session,
in chronological order:

[PROMPT 1 - 00:02:14]
"write a langgraph agent"

[PROMPT 2 - 00:08:45] (after rejecting the first response)
"write a langgraph agent that takes a user question as input,
uses a DuckDuckGo search tool to find relevant information,
summarizes the results using Claude, and handles cases where
the search returns no results by asking the user to rephrase"

[PROMPT 3 - 00:24:11] (after an error in execution)
"the agent is failing when the search tool returns an empty
list. add error handling for this specific case and add a
retry mechanism with exponential backoff"

Evaluate these prompts across:
1. Specificity and clarity (were they vague or precise?)
2. Iteration quality (did prompts improve after failures?)
3. Context inclusion (did they include error messages, expected behavior?)
4. Decomposition (did they break complex tasks into clear sub-goals?)

Return a score from 1-10 and 2-3 sentences of specific feedback.
Format as JSON: { "score": N, "feedback": "..." }

Layer 5: Different Tests, Different Sandboxes
This is the strategic layer most people miss. Not all tests are the same type:
TEST TYPE A: Pure Agentic Workflow
├─ Environment: Python + LangGraph + mock tools
├─ Scoring: Heavy on Prompt Quality, Tool Usage, Agent Design
├─ Sandbox: Full tool access (search, calculator, file reader)
└─ Example: "Build a research agent"

TEST TYPE B: Code + AI Collaboration  
├─ Environment: TypeScript + LLM SDK + real codebase
├─ Scoring: Heavy on Code Quality, Debugging skill
├─ Sandbox: Pre-existing broken codebase to fix
└─ Example: "Debug this AI pipeline and improve its accuracy"

TEST TYPE C: System Design + Prompting
├─ Environment: No code execution — document-based
├─ Scoring: Heavy on architecture thinking, prompt design
├─ Sandbox: Document editor + AI assistant
└─ Example: "Design a multi-agent customer support system"

TEST TYPE D: Data + AI
├─ Environment: Python + Jupyter-style notebook
├─ Scoring: Heavy on data reasoning, prompt engineering
├─ Sandbox: Pre-loaded dataset + model access
└─ Example: "Build a pipeline that classifies customer intent"
Each test type maps to a different Docker image, a different set of available tools, a different scoring rubric for the Agentic Scorer — but the same frontend workspace, the same session recorder, the same score display on the recruiter side.

Build Strategy — Milestones in Strict Order
Milestone 1 — The Dumbest Possible Version That Works
Goal: One candidate, one test type, code runs, score computed, recruiter sees it.
Single Docker image (Python only)
No model selector (Claude only)
No file tree (single file, main.py)
No session recording
Fake scoring (rule-based, not LLM)
No Kubernetes (single server, one container at a time)
Why: proves the loop before you build the sophistication.
Milestone 2 — Real Scoring
Goal: Replace fake scoring with real LLM evaluation.
Prompt Quality Agent (first and most impactful)
Session recorder (need the data to evaluate)
Store events in PostgreSQL
Score stored in DB, retrieved by recruiter
Why: this is your moat. Deploy it the moment it works.
Milestone 3 — Real Sandbox
Goal: Multiple concurrent candidates, safe isolation.
Kubernetes (AWS EKS or GKE)
One pod per candidate
Resource limits enforced
Network proxy for API call logging
Container lifecycle management (spin up on invite, destroy after submit)
Why: before this milestone, you can only demo to one person at a time.
Milestone 4 — Multiple Test Types
Goal: Support TypeScript + Go sandboxes, Notebook type.
Docker image registry (separate image per language)
Test type configuration in DB
Scoring rubric per test type
Model selector (GPT-4o, Claude, Gemini)
Why: opens up your total addressable market beyond Python AI engineers.
Milestone 5 — Session Replay
Goal: Recruiter watches the full session like a video.
Event timeline visualization
Step-through replay (go to any point in time)
See every prompt, every response, every execution
This is your killer demo feature
Why: no competitor has this. It's how you close enterprise deals.

The Technologies You Need to Actually Learn (ordered)
Week 1-2: Container fundamentals

Docker (build, run, volumes, networking)
Docker Compose (local multi-container development)
Linux process isolation (why containers are safe)
Resource limits (cgroups, memory/CPU caps)

Week 3-4: Backend execution layer

WebSocket protocol (bidirectional, low-latency — terminal streams need this)
Node.js child_process / exec (how to run code from a server)
Stream handling (stdout/stderr as streams, not buffered)
Process timeouts and killing zombie processes

Week 5-6: Orchestration

Kubernetes fundamentals (pods, services, deployments)
AWS EKS or Google GKE (managed Kubernetes)
Container registry (ECR or GCR — where your Docker images live)
Horizontal pod autoscaling (scale sandbox count based on demand)

Week 7-8: Agentic evaluation

Anthropic Claude API (messages, system prompts, structured outputs)
Prompt engineering for evaluation (how to get consistent JSON scores)
LangGraph or similar (understand what candidates will be building)
Multi-agent orchestration (your scoring pipeline is itself a multi-agent system)

Week 9+: Production hardening

Network security (VPC, security groups, no candidate can talk to another)
Secrets management (AWS Secrets Manager — API keys never in code)
Observability (logs → CloudWatch, errors → Sentry, metrics → Datadog)
Load testing (what happens when 100 candidates submit simultaneously)


The One Thing That Separates You From Everyone
HackerRank sees: code input → test output. Pass or fail.
You see: every thought the candidate had while building. Every prompt. Every rejection. Every recovery. Every iteration. Every decision.
That's not a code evaluator. That's an intelligence evaluator.
And when a recruiter asks "why did you score Aarav a 92?" — you can show them: "He sent 3 prompts. The first was vague. He rejected it. The second included the error context and expected behavior. He accepted, ran it, hit an edge case, fixed it himself without re-prompting. His error recovery is what pushed him to 92."